<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>
Native American Legends: White Buffalo Calf Woman (Ptesan-Wi)
</H1>




<font size=4>
<b>Name:</B> White Buffalo Calf Woman<BR>
<b>Tribal affiliation:</B> <a href="http://www.bigorrin.org/lakota_kids.htm">Lakota Sioux</a>,
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/dakota_culture.htm">Dakota Sioux</a><BR>
<b>Also known as:</B> White Buffalo Woman, Buffalo Calf Woman, White Buffalo Cow Woman, White Buffalo Calf Maiden<BR>
<b>Native names:</B> Ptesan-Wi, Ptesanwi, Ptesanwin<BR>
<b>Pronunciation:</B> ptay-sahn-ween<BR>
<b>Type:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/goddesses.htm">Native American goddess</a>, 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/culture-heroes.htm">culture hero</a>,
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/legends-buffalo.htm">buffalo spirit</a><BR>
<b>Related figures in other tribes:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/star-boy.htm">Poia</a> (Blackfoot), 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/lone-man.htm">Lone Man</a> (Mandan), 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/glooskap.htm">Gluskap</a> (Wabanaki)<BR>
<BR>
</font>

White Buffalo Calf Woman is one of the most important Sioux mythological figures. She brought the 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/legends-pipe.htm">sacred pipe</a> 
to the Sioux people, and taught them many of the arts of civilization.

<H2><U>
White Buffalo Woman Stories</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.pyramidmesa.com/buffalowoman1.htm
">White Buffalo Calf Woman Brings the First Pipe</a>:</B> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota legend about White Buffalo Woman and the origin of the peace pipe.
<BR>

